{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4be1ffa-d0d2-413a-a4c9-8c6c7896701b","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production-safe low-overhead collection, `cpu-sampling` is the right profile — it uses EventPipe, not a profiler attach.\n- Add `--buffersize 256` if you're seeing dropped events.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f250c4da-7ffd-4cc4-b6fc-1abe43513df8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I should provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"D7C1:2F696B:C4305:E8AE6:69F2B029"},"id":"4d97adb8-c433-4bc4-8e84-16adce38f8f0","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:28:18.508Z","parentId":"0b794763-b6fb-459d-9a01-d702c1aa6842"}
